      Should index funds be illegal?
   =20
 =20

One attraction of index investing is that nobody is responsible for any inv=
esting decisions. If I buy an index fund, I am just following sensible stan=
dard financial advice about indexing and diversification; if that index fun=
d happens to hold stocks in companies that I find objectionable, I can say =
=E2=80=9Cwell that=E2=80=99s not my fault, I didn=E2=80=99t buy those compa=
nies, I just bought the index fund.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile the index fund manag=
er buys those stocks, not because she wants to, but because they are in the=
 index and her mandate is to track the index; buying those stocks is not re=
ally her fault either. Meanwhile the index=C2=A0provider=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the company that compiles the index and licenses it to funds =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0has some quasi-mechanical standards for including stocks in the index=
, and they=C2=A0probably amount to something like =E2=80=9Cthis index inclu=
des all of the stocks in the market,=E2=80=9D or all of the biggest stocks,=
 or all of the tech stocks, or all of the US-based stocks, or all of the Ch=
ina-based stocks, or whatever the index name says. There are indexes that a=
re like =E2=80=9Cthis index includes all of the stocks in the US that we do=
 not find morally objectionable,=E2=80=9D but that is more of a niche produ=
ct than the indexes that are just all of the stocks.
And so in theory you can have a lot of ordinary people investing their mone=
y in companies that they find objectionable, through mutual funds whose man=
agers find them objectionable, based on an index whose compilers find them =
objectionable. Nobody=C2=A0wants=C2=A0to invest in those companies, but nob=
ody is quite=C2=A0responsible=C2=A0for the decision, so they=C2=A0do=C2=A0i=
nvest in those companies.
And, really, that is the point of indexing! The basic idea of index investi=
ng is something like =E2=80=9Cif you try to make investing decisions they w=
ill be bad, so just buy the entire stock market,=E2=80=9D so it is importan=
t for index funds to be set up in such a way that nobody makes investment d=
ecisions. People=C2=A0want=C2=A0to make investment decisions, but those dec=
isions are bad for them, so you have to guard carefully against the tendenc=
y for investment decisions to creep back into the process. At every level, =
you want to make sure that no one is making decisions.
Of course this is exaggerated and we   talk all the   time around   here ab=
out how a lot of discretion=C2=A0does=C2=A0creep back into index compositio=
n, but still the theory makes a certain sense.
Anyway:

The world=E2=80=99s largest asset manager and a top stock-market-index comp=
iler are being investigated by a congressional committee for facilitating A=
merican investment in Chinese companies the U.S. government has accused of =
bolstering China=E2=80=99s military and violating human rights.
The House of Representatives=E2=80=99 Select Committee on the Chinese Commu=
nist Party notified BlackRock and MSCI on Monday of the probes into their a=
ctivities, according to letters viewed by The Wall Street Journal. ...
The panel told the firms that a review of just a sliver of their activities=
=E2=80=94which aren=E2=80=99t illegal=E2=80=94showed that they are causing =
Americans to fund more than 60 Chinese companies that U.S. agencies have fl=
agged on security or human-rights grounds.
By routing =E2=80=9Cmassive flows of American capital=E2=80=9D to such Chin=
ese entities, the U.S. firms are =E2=80=9Cexacerbating an already significa=
nt national-security threat and undermining American values,=E2=80=9D said =
the letters, signed by the panel=E2=80=99s chairman, Republican Rep. Mike G=
allagher of Wisconsin, and its top Democrat, Rep. Raja Krishnamoorthi of Il=
linois. Across five funds, BlackRock has invested more than $429 million in=
 such Chinese companies, the panel found. =E2=80=A6
MSCI selects the securities that make up the indexes many investors use as =
a basis for their portfolios. There are more than $13 trillion of assets be=
nchmarked to MSCI=E2=80=99s products. In a statement, the firm said it=E2=
=80=99s reviewing the committee=E2=80=99s inquiry. It has previously said t=
hat all of its index decisions are made after consultations with a range of=
 global market participants. ...
With this latest investigation into BlackRock and MSCI, the panel is broade=
ning its focus by now also scrutinizing asset managers and index compilers.=
 Such firms would typically have little to no direct involvement with the C=
hinese companies in their portfolios or indexes, but they play a crucial ro=
le in directing large sums of Americans=E2=80=99 retirement savings into th=
eir coffers. The panel said its review has shown that, =E2=80=9Cas a direct=
 result of decisions=E2=80=9D made by BlackRock and MSCI, Americans have be=
en =E2=80=9Cunwittingly funding=E2=80=9D an array of Chinese companies that=
 operate against the interests of the U.S. =E2=80=A6
In its letters, the committee asked each firm to make a full accounting of =
the Chinese entities it is investing in or including on indexes, and to rep=
ort any due diligence it undertakes before doing so.

At some level the correct answer for an index provider is =E2=80=9Cwe do no=
 due diligence on any companies, because if we did that would undermine our=
 complete innocence of any fundamental analysis,=E2=80=9D but nobody wants =
to hear that.=C2=A0
By the way! The solution here, if Congress finds these companies morally ob=
jectionable, is to write a law that is like =E2=80=9Cit is illegal for Amer=
ican funds to invest in these companies.=E2=80=9D If you do that, then MSCI=
, in its =E2=80=9Cconsultations with a range of global market participants,=
=E2=80=9D will hear things like =E2=80=9Cwe need an index of Chinese compan=
ies that we are allowed to invest in,=E2=80=9D and it will duly compile tha=
t sort of index, and BlackRock will invest in it.=C2=A0Congress=C2=A0can go=
 ahead and make investing decisions for MSCI.=C2=A0

