There is a simple model of private equity in which private equity firms cre=
ate value for their investors by=C2=A0taking=C2=A0it from creditors. There =
is some boring company with steady cash flows and some investment-grade deb=
t, and a private equity firm comes along and buys it by loading it down wit=
h a lot more debt. The existing creditors had safe investment-grade debt, b=
ut now they have risky claims on a much more levered business; the value of=
 their debt has gone down. The new creditors are also making a risky bet, t=
hough at least they get paid for it. If things work out, the company does w=
ell and the private equity fund makes a multiple of its capital; the credit=
ors just get paid back. If things don=E2=80=99t work out, the company goes =
bankrupt, the private equity fund loses its investment but the creditors al=
so take big losses. If things first work out and then don=E2=80=99t, then t=
he private equity fund can take out a big dividend in the good times and ma=
ke back its investment, and then in the bad times it can leave the creditor=
s with the losses. And the private equity sponsor is smart and focused on t=
his, so it will write its debt documents in ways that allow it to get its m=
oney back and leave creditors with the losses.
I don=E2=80=99t mean to endorse this model completely, but a lot of people =
believe some version of it. In particular, a=C2=A0lot=C2=A0of people believ=
e a version of it where you replace the words =E2=80=9Cthe private equity f=
und=E2=80=9D with the word =E2=80=9CApollo.=E2=80=9D Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Al=
lison McNeely  writes about Apollo Global Management Inc.=E2=80=99s image:
Apollo=E2=80=99s longtime reputation =E2=80=94 particularly in the brass-kn=
uckle business of bickering over bankruptcies and investing in troubled com=
panies =E2=80=93 has had real financial consequences. Historically, bond an=
d loan investors have demanded additional interest, around 50 to 100 basis =
points, to finance Apollo=E2=80=99s leveraged buyouts, just in case a brawl=
 ensues. It=E2=80=99s known as the =E2=80=9CApollo Premium.=E2=80=9D
I mean in some sense that should be a source of pride? Sure you pay an extr=
a 50 to 100 basis points to finance your buyouts, but that=E2=80=99s only b=
ecause you have extracted so much more value for your investors =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0from your creditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0than all the other private equity =
firms. They left money on the table in their previous deals. You took all t=
he money off all the tables in all your deals, and you pay for it now.
