" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The world=E2=80=99s largest asset manager and =
a top stock-market-index compiler are being investigated by a congressional=
 committee for facilitating American investment in Chinese companies the U.=
S. government has accused of bolstering China=E2=80=99s military and violat=
ing human rights.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The House of Representatives=E2=80=99 Select C=
ommittee on the Chinese Communist Party notified BlackRock and MSCI on Mond=
ay of the probes into their activities, according to letters viewed by The =
Wall Street Journal. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The panel told the firms that a review of just=
 a sliver of their activities=E2=80=94which aren=E2=80=99t illegal=E2=80=94=
showed that they are causing Americans to fund more than 60 Chinese compani=
es that U.S. agencies have flagged on security or human-rights grounds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By routing =E2=80=9Cmassive flows of American =
capital=E2=80=9D to such Chinese entities, the U.S. firms are =E2=80=9Cexac=
erbating an already significant national-security threat and undermining Am=
erican values,=E2=80=9D said the letters, signed by the panel=E2=80=99s cha=
irman, Republican Rep. Mike Gallagher of Wisconsin, and its top Democrat, R=
ep. Raja Krishnamoorthi of Illinois. Across five funds, BlackRock has inves=
ted more than $429 million in such Chinese companies, the panel found. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MSCI selects the securities that make up the i=
ndexes many investors use as a basis for their portfolios. There are more t=
han $13 trillion of assets benchmarked to MSCI=E2=80=99s products. In a sta=
tement, the firm said it=E2=80=99s reviewing the committee=E2=80=99s inquir=
y. It has previously said that all of its index decisions are made after co=
nsultations with a range of global market participants. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With this latest investigation into BlackRock =
and MSCI, the panel is broadening its focus by now also scrutinizing asset =
managers and index compilers. Such firms would typically have little to no =
direct involvement with the Chinese companies in their portfolios or indexe=
s, but they play a crucial role in directing large sums of Americans=E2=80=
=99 retirement savings into their coffers. The panel said its review has sh=
own that, =E2=80=9Cas a direct result of decisions=E2=80=9D made by BlackRo=
ck and MSCI, Americans have been =E2=80=9Cunwittingly funding=E2=80=9D an a=
rray of Chinese companies that operate against the interests of the U.S. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In its letters, the committee asked each firm =
to make a full accounting of the Chinese entities it is investing in or inc=
luding on indexes, and to report any due diligence it undertakes before doi=
ng so.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some level the correct answer for an index =
provider is =E2=80=9Cwe do no due diligence on any companies, because if we=
 did that would undermine our complete innocence of any fundamental analysi=
s,=E2=80=9D but nobody wants to hear that.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way! The solution here, if Congress fin=
ds these companies morally objectionable, is to write a law that is like =
=E2=80=9Cit is illegal for American funds to invest in these companies.=E2=
=80=9D If you do that, then MSCI, in its =E2=80=9Cconsultations with a rang=
e of global market participants,=E2=80=9D will hear things like =E2=80=9Cwe=
 need an index of Chinese companies that we are allowed to invest in,=E2=80=
=9D and it will duly compile that sort of index, and BlackRock will invest =
in it.=C2=A0<em>Congress=C2=A0</em>can go ahead and make investing decision=
s for MSCI.=C2=A0</p>
