n=E2=80=99t get to exchange your 138 MattCoins for real money again. There =
is not actually a pot with $100 in it; I just took the $100!=C2=A0You put i=
n $100 and got back a pile of magic beans that are not redeemable for anyth=
ing. The pile grew bigger over the year, but it remains worthless.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">More than $138. You put in $100 for 100 Ma=
ttCoins, those MattCoins offered a 38% yield, other people see that 38% yie=
ld and said =E2=80=9CI want some of that,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>they </em>buy s=
ome MattCoins, the price of MattCoin rises, still other people see the risi=
ng=C2=A0<em>price=C2=A0</em>and say =E2=80=9Cooh I want some of=C2=A0<em>th=
at</em>,=E2=80=9D the price rises further, it=E2=80=99s a virtuous cycle, e=
ventually each MattCoin is worth like $10,000 and your 138 MattCoins make y=
ou a millionaire.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that Answer 3 is the standard answer t=
hat traditional financial analysis would give you: You bought an electronic=
 token with no cash flows ever, so it=E2=80=99s worth zero. I am drawn to t=
his traditional analysis, but it has not really worked all that well for un=
derstanding crypto.</p>
