<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Apollogies</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a simple model of private equity in w=
hich private equity firms create value for their investors by=C2=A0<em>taki=
ng=C2=A0</em>it from creditors. There is some boring company with steady ca=
sh flows and some investment-grade debt, and a private equity firm comes al=
ong and buys it by loading it down with a lot more debt. The existing credi=
tors had safe investment-grade debt, but now they have risky claims on a mu=
ch more levered business; the value of their debt has gone down. The new cr=
editors are also making a risky bet, though at least they get paid for it. =
If things work out, the company does well and the private equity fund makes=
 a multiple of its capital; the creditors just get paid back. If things don=
=E2=80=99t work out, the company goes bankrupt, the private equity fund los=
es its investment but the creditors also take big losses. If things first w=
ork out and then don=E2=80=99t, then the private equity fund can take out a=
 big dividend in the good times and make back its investment, and then in t=
he bad times it can leave the creditors with the losses. And the private eq=
uity sponsor is smart and focused on this, so it will write its debt docume=
nts in ways that allow it to get its money back and leave creditors with th=
e losses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t mean to endorse this model com=
pletely, but a lot of people believe some version of it. In particular, a=
=C2=A0lot=C2=A0of people believe a version of it where you replace the word=
s =E2=80=9Cthe private equity fund=E2=80=9D with the word =E2=80=9CApollo.=
=E2=80=9D Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Allison McNeely <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/32262470.263416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMDEvYXBvbGxvLXRyaWVzLXRvLXNoZWQtcnV0aGxlc3=
MtcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktaW1hZ2UtaW4tbWFyYy1yb3dhbi1lcmE_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgwMTIzX=
01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rl=
cm09MjMwODAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB38578=
01d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> writes about Apollo Global Management Inc.=E2=80=99s image</a=
>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Apollo=E2=80=99s longtime reputati=
on =E2=80=94 particularly in the brass-knuckle business of bickering over b=
ankruptcies and investing in troubled companies =E2=80=93 has had real fina=
ncial consequences. Historically, bond and loan investors have demanded add=
itional interest, around 50 to 100 basis points, to finance Apollo=E2=80=99=
s leveraged buyouts, just in case a brawl ensues. It=E2=80=99s known as the=
 =E2=80=9CApollo Premium.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean in some sense that should be a source o=
f pride? Sure you pay an extra 50 to 100 basis points to finance your buyou=
ts, but that=E2=80=99s only because you have extracted so much more value f=
or your investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0from your creditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0than al=
l the other private equity firms. They left money on the table in their pre=
vious deals. You took all the money off all the tables in all your deals, a=
nd you pay for it now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway though the point of the article is that=
 Apollo is now=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>primarily a private equity firm focus=
ed on extracting value from creditors. Now it is mostly a creditor:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since he was named chief executive officer, [M=
arc]<strong>=C2=A0</strong>Rowan, 60, has acknowledged what many in the ind=
ustry have been feeling in their bones: The traditional private equity busi=
ness, the one Apollo mastered over three decades, isn=E2=80=99t what it use=
d to be now that those golden years of near-zero interest rates are over. H=
e=E2=80=99s been pushing Apollo further and further beyond its private equi=
ty roots and into high-growth arenas like private credit and insurance. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Call Apollo a =E2=80=9Cprivate equity firm=E2=
=80=9D these days and executives will correct you: No, we=E2=80=99re an alt=
ernative asset management company, one that=E2=80=99s driving into direct l=
ending, structured credit and more, powered by Rowan=E2=80=99s financial ma=
sterstroke, the insurance arm Athene.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the same time, Rowan is also chasing a more=
 elusive goal, and one that=E2=80=99s difficult to quantify in dollars and =
cents. He wants Apollo to shake off its image as one of Wall Street=E2=80=
=99s most ruthless risk-takers for good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Executives have spent the past few years on wh=
at some competitors have snarkily called an =E2=80=9CApollo Apology Tour.=
=E2=80=9D Even now, they often start meetings with prospective clients by f=
ielding questions about their reputation as a hard-driving investor and are=
 putting more effort into explaining their business, Apollo insiders say. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt is up to us now, over this next pe=
riod of time, to actually change the perception for the reality of what the=
 business is,=E2=80=9D Rowan said at the Economic Club of New York lunch. =
=E2=80=9CWe are primarily an investment-grade provider of private credit.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you build a reputation for extracting a lot=
 of battle by being cleverer, harder-working and more ruthless than everyon=
e else, well, in large swathes of finance that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0just=C2=A0<em=
>good</em>. Investors will want to give you money, because you are clever a=
nd ruthless. People will want to work for you, because they fancy themselve=
s clever and ruthless, and because you pay well. Creditors will fear you, w=
hich is not all good (you have to pay them more to finance your deals), but=
 which is maybe helpful if you actually=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>end up fighti=
ng with them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you are an investment-grade provider of=
 private credit, that reputation is mostly unhelpful. If you=C2=A0go to an =
investment-grade company and say =E2=80=9Chey we would love to provide you =
with some investment-grade private credit=E2=80=9D and their first reaction=
 is =E2=80=9Cokay but you plan to kill us right,=E2=80=9D you will not get =
a lot of deals done. Lots of companies raise money from people who obviousl=
y plan to kill them, but that=E2=80=99s <em>distressed</em> credit and they=
 have no choices; if you want to deploy lots of capital doing investment-gr=
ade deals it is helpful to have a reputation for being=C2=A0<em>easy=C2=A0<=
/em>to deal with, not terrifying. If you=E2=80=99re an Apollo credit person=
, you probably do have to start every meeting by saying =E2=80=9Cno, I=E2=
=80=99m not like our private-equity guys, I=E2=80=99m nice, we sit on diffe=
rent floors, I=E2=80=99m scared of them too.=E2=80=9D</p>
